\introduction  %% \introduction[modified heading if necessary]

Population and economic growth, alongside demographic changes, is expected to cause a dramatic increase in global food demand over the coming decades \citep{}. At the same time increasing GDP tends to result in population consuming more calories in total, with animal calories making up a greater proportion of the overall food consumption \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. Meanwhile climate change is expected to affect the current food production in complex ways \citep{}. To meet the growing demand for food it will be necessary for agricultural systems to dramatically increase production \citep{}. Since the area of land available for food production will be constrained by human activities such as urbanization, infrastructure development and bioenergy production as well as declining soil quality \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}, the importance of agricultural intensification will play increasingly important roles in achieving global food security. However, the various management practices required to increase crop yield, such as irrigation, fertilizer and mechanization, are associated with environmental degradation which reduces the sustainability and resilience of the food supply system \citep[e.g.][]{}. Thus, accurate modelling the environmental impact of future agricultural expansion and intensification is essential in order to assess the sustainability of global food security \citep{}. In a world in which food is consumed..., it is necessary to consider the complex feedbacks between food production and the global macroeconomy. \\

The Global Change Assessment Model (GCAM) \citep{}, an integrated assessment model (IAM), has been developed to gain insight into coupled human-natural systems and simulate their ``co-evolution in the future'' \citep{le-page_downscaling_2016}. The model is divided into coupled subsystems representing the global economy, energy systems, agriculture and land use. GCAM is used extensively to simulate the response of terrestrial systems to exogenous factors such as population growth, technological improvements and economic and environmental policies \citep[e.g.][]{}. In many cases GCAM may be used successfully as a standalone model \citep[e.g.][]{}. Alternatively, it may be coupled with domain-specific models to assess the impacts of change on particular sectors. An important feature of GCAM is the detailed representation of the agricultural sector and its relationship with other sectors in the global economy \citep{}. Output from the land system component of GCAM, which simulates land use activities and the production of major crops, is at the subregional level and must be spatially downscaled in order to use with gridded impact assessment models \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. Coupling these two classes of models is recognised as an important technical challenge \citep{nazemi_on_2015}. However, existing downscaling routines typically consider cropland as a homogeneous class and do not provide information about land use intensity or specific management practices such as irrigation and multiple cropping \citep{}. \\

A recent addition to GCAM is a land use model to downscale predictions about land use and land cover, GCAMLU \citep{le-page_downscaling_2016}. The algorithm follows an ordered approach in which land use and land cover types, as well as agricultural production activities \citep{}, are spatially downscaled in order of decreasing economic value \citep{}. A feature of the model is the inclusion of a user-defined target level of intensification versus expansion of agricultural land. The model attempts to meet the specified demand while also satisfying the requirements of non-agricultural land use types. Additional parameters define transition priorities and spatial constaints. The algorithm is based on the assumption that change from one land use expansion tends to occur in areas where the land use is already present \citep[e.g.][]{}. This effect is represented by calculating the ``kernel density'' for each land use type, which represents the proximity and density of a land use around a grid cell. The suitability of grid cells to agricultural land is additionally based on nutrient availability and soil workability according to the Harmonised World Soil Database \citep{}. While GCAMLU is an appropriate solution for various types of environmental change studies, it lacks the appropriate level of detail for assessing environmental impacts of agricultural intensification \citep{}. For example, the model does not explicitly represent crop rotations, nor does it include important management practices such as irrigation and agricultural intensity. These factors limit its application in impact assessment models \citep{}. \\

A number of previous authors have approached the problem. \citet{hurtt2001} developed a simple downscaling procedure for the IPCC 5th Assessment Report in which grid level estimates of crop area from \citep{ref} were scaled with national level estimates of change. Several impact assessment models contain inbuilt downscaling routines. However, while such methods may be suitable for hindcasting, when intensification is reversed, they are less well suited to future simulations because it does not account for the spatial and temporal heterogeneity of biophysical constraints on future crop production. The Model of Agricultural Production and its Impact on the Environment (MAgPIE) \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008} is a global land use optimisation model which consists of a regional demand model coupled with a gridded supply model (the LPJmL model \citep{}). An inbuilt land use model determines the spatial allocation of various agricultural production activities by minimizing the total cost of production of a given regional demand \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. The production cost, which is defined in terms of cost per unit food energy, varies spatially as a result of differences in potential yield between grid cells \citep{lotze-campen_global_2014}. \\

In this paper we develop a computationally efficient algorithm to spatially downscale crop production data from GCAM. The main output from the model is a time series of maps showing the spatial distribution of specific crops (e.g. rice, wheat, maize) at four input levels (subsistence, low input rainfed, high input rainfed and high input irrigated). The remainder of this paper is divided into four sections. First, we provide a brief overview of the GCAM model with particular emphasis on its representation of the agricultural sector and its links and feedbacks with other system components. We then describe the downscaling algorithm and its data requirements, as well as describing the pre-processing to transform the raw input data prior to a simulation. We demonstrate the model through an example application to India; a region which provides a useful testbed for the concept and implementation of the model because of its complex agricultural systems and projected population and socioeconomic change. Lastly, we discuss the limitations of the model, highlight potential use cases and identify areas for improvement, before drawing brief conclusions. \\

