The principal model input is regional crop production values from the GCAM simulation. Initial crop area maps are provided by the MapSPAM product \citet{you_generating_2014}; a state of the art dataset which shows the spatial distribution of 42 crops around the year 2005. Yield maps, which are part of the MapSPAM database, translate crop production in each cell to crop area. A unique feature of this dataset compared to other similar datasets is the fact that it differentiates between irrigated and rainfed and high, intermediate and subsistence input levels \citep{you_generating_2014}. GCAM explicitly models 3 single crop classes (Rice, Wheat, Maize) and 8 aggregated crop classes (...), each containing several subcrops. We use the MapSPAM production data to disaggregate these crop classes, initially assuming that the proportion of subcrops within the main crop class remains the same during the simulation period. This assumption is relaxed during runtime if the specified production cannot be met. This allows for the fact that some subcrops may have reached their peak production while others have greater potential for upscaling. Crop calendars from AQUASTAT and MIRCA2000 \citep{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010} are used to temporally disaggregate crop production maps into growing seasons. \\

The model algorithm is constrained by available cropland at each time point, allowing it to implicitly balance extensification and intensification processes to meet regional food demand. Future maps of cropland extent are retrieved from GCAMLU \citep{le-page_downscaling_2016}; a land use change model specifically designed to downscale land use/land cover change from GCAM. A one-way coupling mechanism is adopted whereby output from GCAMLU is used as an input to the present downscaling algorithm at each time point. \\

\subsection{Downscaling algorithm}

The downscaling algorithm is based on the assumption that an increase in the production of a particular crop is more likely to happen in grid cells with a high suitability and neighbourhood influence, whereas a fall in production will tend to occur in grid cells with relatively low suitability values and/or a low neighbourhood influence. Suitability is calculated according to the revenue model proposed by \citet{you_generating_2014}, which is expressed

\begin{equation}
Rev_{i,j,l} = Price_{j} \times Access_{i,j} \times PotYield_{i,j,l}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Rev$ is revenue, $Access$ is market accessibility, $PotYield$ is potential yield and $i$, $j$, $l$ are indices representing pixel, crop type and input level, respectively. We obtain estimates of potential yield from the Food and Agriculture Organization Global Agro-Ecological Zones (FAO GAEZ) database \citep{fischer}. Following \citet{you_generating_2014}, we approximate market accessibility with future estimates of population density at 5 arcminute $\times$ 5 arcminute spatial resolution \citep{jones_population_2016}. We use an arbitrary value for the price of crops because it does not influence the relative suitability of pixels within the same crop class. Neighbourhood influence is the mean area of crop i,j,l within a 3 $\times$ 3 neighbourhood. \\

We assume that crop production can be increased either by expanding the area of land devoted to growing the crop or by intensifying agricultural production in order to increase crop yield \citep{lotzecampen_impacts_2014}. The former can be achieved by converting existing cropland previously allocated to another crop or by converting non-agricultural land to cropland, while the latter is achieved by increasing the use of the main inputs (e.g. water, fertilizer, labour, technology) that enable crop growth. These physical processes are expressed in the downscaling algorithm as three separate routines. The first of these routines simulates the \textit{conversion} of land with with decreasing regional production to crops with increasing production. The second routine simulates the \textit{expansion} of land to unallocated cropland, which is controlled by the output from GCAMLU and the fraction of land that must be kept fallow during a growing season. The last routine models the \textit{intensification} of existing agricultural land. \\

The algorithm downscales each crop type in turn following a user-supplied hierarchy which is supposed to reflect the perceived relative economic value of the various crops. This approach, which is used in various spatially explicit land use change models \citep[e.g.][]{fuchs_high-resolution_2013,moulds_an_2015,le-page_downscaling_2016}, removes the need to dynamically simulate competition between crop types, resulting in a stable and computationally efficient algorithm. [Note: If possible, the user should only supply the order of GCAM PFTs, with the order of sub-crops determined endogenously]. A rotational constraint parameter is introduced to define the maximum allowable fraction of available cropland in a grid cell \citep{lotze-campen_global_2008}. \\

% *Simplify the problem*
Convert area belonging to crops with decreasing regional production to a holding class denoting the input level (e.g. unallocated high-input irrigated cropland). We assume that a fall in production is predominantly achieved by converting cropland to another crop category rather than through de-intensification. Conversion to unallocated cropland takes place in an ordered way [The actual order does not matter]. Pixels containing the crop are arranged in order of suitability. Each pixel/input-level combination is considered as a separate entity with a unique suitability value (i.e. pixel A, high-input rainfed is considered as separate from pixel A, low-input rainfed). Starting with the pixel with the lowest suitability, a small amount of land is subtracted from the area of the crop in the pixel. The quantity removed is multiplied by the yield value for the pixel \textit{i}, input-level \textit{j} and subtracted from the total amount by which the regional production has to fall. Optionally, this process can be made stochastic in which case the conversion is only made if the suitability value is lower than a number between zero and one drawn from a uniform random distribution. \\

% *Set a target intensification*
Having dealt with crop types with falling regional production, the algorithm moves on to consider crops with increasing regional production. A first round of intensification is initiated in which the algorithm attempts to achieve a user supplied target. This could specify, for instance, that 25\% of the increase in wheat production should come from intensification. Crops are considered in order. Pixels are arranged according to the suitability of the highest input level present in the pixel. The intensification module shifts a small amount of land up one input level. The change in production is calculated and subtracted from the regional target. This process continues until the target intensification is met, or no more intensification is possible. \\

% *Extensification*
The next part of the allocation routine attempts to allocate the outstanding crop production through the process of extensification. Pixels containing unallocated cropland are selected and the corresponding suitability value compared to a random number drawn from a uniform random distribution. If the test is successful, a small area of unallocated cropland is assigned to the crop under consideration. This process continues either until the production target for the crop is met or until there is no more suitable and unallocated cropland.\\

% *Additional round of intensification*
Lastly, a second round of intensification is applied to crops which have not met their regional production target (for this reason there may be more intensification than the target). As in the first round, pixels are selected until the regional production target is met. In cases where this is still not possible we assume that the region cannot achieve the target production value and the unallocated amount is distributed evenly between the other subcrops within the main crop. If this has been done for any subcrop the algorithm returns to the top of the allocation routine (the first round of intensification) and repeats the allocation process. Otherwise, the algorithm moves to the next time point. \\

