\subsection{Discussion}

A number of dynamic factors influence the suitability of land to particular crops. The MapSPAM potential yield product, which informs our estimation of crop suitability and is key to the allocation process, only considers biophysical constraints for the contemporary period. Over time, factors such as soil erosion, salinisation, waterlogging and groundwater depletion, which often arise due to unsustainable agricultural intensification, may decrease the potential crop yield in many areas and hence simultaneously reduce the likelihood of crop expansion as well as reducing the yield of crops currently grown in those areas. Meanwhile social constraints on production such as access to labour may also change over time, particularly in regions where there is rapid socioeconomic change. At present none of these dynamic constaints are considered in the downscaling framework. Incorporating biophysical constraints will require the addition of an Earth system model which is capable of representing the various processes. More challenging will be the inclusion of socioeconomic constraints... There are many constraints on the output of individual farms which cannot be considered explicitly. Ultimately, change in production at the regional level is the aggregate effect of changes at the level of individual farms.  \\

Climate change and socioeconomic development will affect crop yield \citep{iizumi_responses_2017}. A simplistic approach is used to account for the former, while the latter is currently not considered. The FAO GAEZ methodology in theory provides... However, data access to this resource is challenging. In our view, improving the interface to spatial input data would improve the ability of researchers... Moreover, opening the source code used for generating the datasest would be a... which would improve the ability of researchers to update the dataset according to their specific needs. \\

The model requires a large amount of data in order to provide meaningful results. As the case study demonstrates, a degree of familiarity with agriculture in the region under consideration is necessary. \\

The model follows an ordered approach which is computationally efficient but fails to represent competition between crop classes. Thus, an important input to the model is the order in which crops are allocated. Uncertainty may be accounted for by stochastically changing the order of crop allocation over several runs in order to build up a probability distribution describing the spatial distribution of various crops. These can either be combined in some way or used in subsequent analyses as a probabilistic input... The relative speed with which simulations can be carried out facilitate such an approach. \\

Separate treatment of land use constraints in GCAM and the downscaling algorithm may give rise to inconsistencies. Integrated models such as MAgPIE include representations of both the macroeconomy and land use. Coupling GCAM with a spatially-explicit land use change model would allow for more detailed consideration of the various constaints on agricultural production and the feedbacks to other parts of the macroeconomy system [...] Eventually dynamically couple with an integrated assessment framework in order to assess the change in model output [...] An important design feature is to ensure the algorithm is computationally efficient and \textit{fast}, enabling rapid generation of multiple scenarios of agricultural land use change. This design paradigm aligns with that of integrated assessment models, which are usually run multiple times [thousands - provide reference?] with varying initialisations and parameter values in order to capture uncertainty. Future developments should adhere to this philosophy to ensure its continued applicability to global change research. \\

